description: Latin obtundere (“to dull", "deaden", "deafen”), from ob- (see ob-) + tundere. More at obtuse.

verbs.description: obtund (third-person singular simple present obtunds, present participle obtunding, simple past and past participle obtunded)

entries.meaning: (transitive, chiefly medicine) To reduce the edge or effects of; to mitigate; to dull.
